If formula_3 and formula_183 are normed spaces, they are isomorphic normed spaces if there exists a linear bijection formula_184 such that formula_185 and its inverse formula_220 are continuous. If one of the two spaces formula_3 or formula_183 is complete (or reflexive, separable, etc.) then so is the other space. Two normed spaces formula_3 and formula_183 are isometrically isomorphic if in addition, formula_185 is an isometry, that is, formula_226 for every formula_28 in formula_140 The Banach‚ÄìMazur distance formula_229 between two isomorphic but not isometric spaces formula_3 and formula_183 gives a measure of how much the two spaces formula_3 and formula_183 differ.

Every continuous linear operator is a bounded linear operator and if dealing only with normed spaces then the converse is also true. That is, a linear operator between two normed spaces is bounded if and only if it is a continuous function. So in particular, because the scalar field (which is formula_64 or formula_7) is a normed space, a linear functional on a normed space is a bounded linear functional if and only if it is a continuous linear functional. This allows for continuity-related results (like those below) to be applied to Banach spaces. Although boundedness is the same as continuity for linear maps between normed spaces, the term "bounded" is more commonly used when dealing primarily with Banach spaces.

If formula_236 is a subadditive function (such as a norm, a sublinear function, or real linear functional), then formula_237 is continuous at the origin if and only if formula_237 is uniformly continuous on all of formula_3; and if in addition formula_240 then formula_237 is continuous if and only if its absolute value formula_242 is continuous, which happens if and only if formula_243 is an open subset of formula_140 
And very importantly for applying the Hahn‚ÄìBanach theorem, a linear functional formula_237 is continuous if and only if this is true of its real part formula_246 and moreover, formula_247 and the real part formula_246 completely determines formula_249 which is why the Hahn‚ÄìBanach theorem is often stated only for real linear functionals.
Also, a linear functional formula_237 on formula_3 is continuous if and only if the seminorm formula_252 is continuous, which happens if and only if there exists a continuous seminorm formula_253 such that formula_254; this last statement involving the linear functional formula_237 and seminorm formula_116 is encountered in many versions of the Hahn‚ÄìBanach theorem.

